WEBVTT

00:13.013 --> 00:15.015
(insects chirping)

00:18.018 --> 00:20.020
(owl hooting softly)

00:30.156 --> 00:32.158
(bell ringing)

00:34.326 --> 00:36.328
♪ ♪

00:40.791 --> 00:42.877
-Help!
-(bell continues ringing)

00:42.918 --> 00:44.712
I'm here! I'm here!

00:44.754 --> 00:46.547
Digging!

00:46.589 --> 00:49.300
Help! Someone's buried alive!

00:49.341 --> 00:52.219
Over here!

00:52.261 --> 00:55.055
Help! Help!

00:58.350 --> 01:01.771
(panting)

01:01.812 --> 01:03.814
What?

01:19.079 --> 01:21.332
♪ ♪

01:49.151 --> 01:51.237
♪ ♪

01:51.278 --> 01:54.824
Whiskey!

01:54.865 --> 01:59.036
The one damned thing
this country does right.

01:59.078 --> 02:02.331
'Cause treating us Irish folk
is definitely not on the list.

02:02.373 --> 02:04.041
I'll drink to that.

02:04.083 --> 02:06.961
From one second-class immigrant
to another.

02:07.002 --> 02:09.213
(laughs) I love ya.

02:09.255 --> 02:12.007
Donald, you want to join?

02:12.049 --> 02:14.510
Donald! (chuckles)

02:17.555 --> 02:21.308
Lookie here,
he's had a head start.

02:21.350 --> 02:24.144
We'll be back, Donny boy.
But for now?

02:24.186 --> 02:26.105
Ah, whiskey.

02:26.146 --> 02:28.107
Come on.

02:28.148 --> 02:31.569
(singing incoherently)

02:36.031 --> 02:38.033
(lively music playing inside)

02:39.994 --> 02:43.122
(people cheering inside)

02:43.163 --> 02:46.709
Hey! Must be Padraig's Day.

02:50.504 --> 02:52.214
HARE:
It's November!

02:52.256 --> 02:55.050
I know. My point is there must
be a reason for the party.

02:55.092 --> 02:56.677
There's no reason
to need a reason.

02:56.719 --> 02:57.845
Aye, well said.

02:57.887 --> 02:59.680
Jamie!

02:59.722 --> 03:01.640
(rhythmic whooping, clapping)

03:07.229 --> 03:10.774
-(cheering)
-(lively music continues)

03:13.527 --> 03:15.529
(laughs)

03:16.655 --> 03:19.575
(laughs)

03:19.617 --> 03:23.787
The little fella sure can
move his... his foot.

03:23.829 --> 03:26.165
BURKE:
Whittles at a pub again?

03:26.206 --> 03:28.500
I imagine the ladies love you
for your big knife.

03:36.550 --> 03:40.012
-(music ends)
-A cheer for the wee lad, Jamie!

03:40.054 --> 03:41.931
(cheering)

03:41.972 --> 03:43.515
Yeah!

03:43.557 --> 03:46.018
SHOLTO:
A cheer for all!

03:46.060 --> 03:48.354
(cheering)

03:48.395 --> 03:52.191
Enjoy this round, people,
courtesy of yours truly!

03:52.232 --> 03:53.692
(cheering)

03:53.734 --> 03:56.195
(chanting):
Sholto! Sholto! Sholto!

03:56.236 --> 04:00.032
-(lively music playing)
-(laughing)

04:00.074 --> 04:03.494
There's that Sholto. He's up
there buying the house drinks.

04:03.535 --> 04:05.287
Hey, bless him.

04:05.329 --> 04:07.289
Hey, it's a bit of a slap
in the face, isn't it?

04:07.331 --> 04:08.707
He owes me 11 shillings.

04:08.749 --> 04:10.125
They're free.
All that matters is...

04:10.167 --> 04:12.461
-11 shillings.
-For what?

04:12.503 --> 04:14.213
He's not very good at cards.

04:16.382 --> 04:18.384
Well, he's right there,
isn't he?

04:23.806 --> 04:25.933
(both whooping)

04:25.975 --> 04:28.394
(crowd cheering)

04:30.437 --> 04:32.439
(Hare laughing)

04:35.442 --> 04:38.112
Now 11 shillings, you great cow.

04:38.153 --> 04:40.739
-Oh, was it that much?
-11.

04:40.781 --> 04:42.992
-Or one.
-One what?

04:43.033 --> 04:47.830
HARE: Yeah, one cut,
right through your eye, boy.

04:47.871 --> 04:49.456
SHOLTO:
All right, all right.

04:49.498 --> 04:51.667
-Easy.
-(lips smack)

04:51.709 --> 04:53.669
Plus interest,
for my friend's suffering.

04:53.711 --> 04:55.421
Or maybe he'll
slice you up anyway.

04:55.462 --> 04:57.214
No, no, no, no, please.

04:57.256 --> 04:59.299
(sighs)

04:59.341 --> 05:03.512
If you'll indulge me, gentlemen,
I have a business proposition

05:03.554 --> 05:06.473
that will make that
look a pittance.

05:06.515 --> 05:10.436
But, um, in private, please.

05:13.272 --> 05:14.606
(clears throat)

05:16.984 --> 05:19.611
(lively music continues)

05:23.991 --> 05:27.453
-And all in the name of science.
-Until you get caught.

05:27.494 --> 05:29.705
A corpse technically
isn't property,

05:29.747 --> 05:31.707
so we're not stealing.

05:31.749 --> 05:33.959
-Uh, legally speaking,
it's just...
-HARE: Trespassing.

05:34.001 --> 05:36.920
Which is why we get creative.

05:36.962 --> 05:39.923
They set up a watchtower,
we go under.

05:39.965 --> 05:42.760
-Tunnels.
-Exactly.

05:42.801 --> 05:46.513
The doctors in Surgeon's Square,
they pay for every body,

05:46.555 --> 05:48.348
no matter the condition.

05:48.390 --> 05:52.186
You see, they're in a-a race
to cure the diseases,

05:52.227 --> 05:54.104
and they need bodies to study.

05:54.146 --> 05:57.983
Now, Robert Knox,
he's my doc on the inside.

05:58.025 --> 06:01.320
And you're cutting us
in because...?

06:01.361 --> 06:03.697
-Well, start with the knife.
-Good point.

06:03.739 --> 06:05.532
And?

06:05.574 --> 06:08.660
My crew are not exactly
responsible types.

06:08.702 --> 06:12.664
Look, they don't always show up.
I-I need two I can count on.

06:12.706 --> 06:15.667
Right?

06:15.709 --> 06:17.294
When and where?

06:17.336 --> 06:19.671
Two hours. Charity Workhouse.

06:19.713 --> 06:22.549
-Whorehouse?
-Oh, that's the charity.

06:22.591 --> 06:24.343
-(chuckles)
-I'm going there now.

06:24.384 --> 06:28.222
That's for the debt
and the drinks.

06:31.517 --> 06:33.769
-(music ends)
-(applause)

06:38.982 --> 06:41.193
Grave robbing.

06:41.235 --> 06:43.028
Is that what it's come to,
is it?

06:43.070 --> 06:44.696
Digging dead bodies
out of the ground.

06:44.738 --> 06:46.573
They're dead, Billy.
They have no opinion.

06:46.615 --> 06:51.203
Listen, we can make more working
one night in the ground

06:51.245 --> 06:53.539
than six months on the docks,

06:53.580 --> 06:55.415
and you're afraid of what?
Of what?

06:55.457 --> 06:57.793
-The magistrate?
-Yeah, the magistrate.

06:57.835 --> 07:00.671
-And the Good Lord.
-(laughs) The Good Lord.

07:00.712 --> 07:04.174
"The Good Lord," he says.
Hmm. (exhales)

07:04.216 --> 07:06.677
Let God have his go in Heaven.

07:06.718 --> 07:11.306
Let me handle things here,
in the actual Earth, all right?

07:11.348 --> 07:13.559
We can't just go
steal dead bodies out...

07:13.600 --> 07:14.768
Yeah...

07:14.810 --> 07:17.813
Bodies, theoretically.

07:21.024 --> 07:23.360
Donald?

07:28.615 --> 07:31.243
Donald, is you
all right there, mate?

07:34.621 --> 07:37.624
Shit. Poor chap.

07:37.666 --> 07:40.711
-(sighs)
-How long has he been dead?

07:40.752 --> 07:42.713
(sighs)
Long enough, I suppose.

07:42.754 --> 07:45.924
With no family to speak of.

07:45.966 --> 07:48.218
Better get him to a hospital.

07:48.260 --> 07:51.180
Aye. Hospital.

07:51.221 --> 07:55.809
Or... to a surgeon?

07:57.102 --> 08:00.606
For a small fee, of course.

08:00.647 --> 08:02.900
(scoffs softly)

08:02.941 --> 08:04.943
(whispers):
In the name of science.

08:08.822 --> 08:10.824
♪ ♪

08:29.968 --> 08:31.929
Is this the right one?

08:31.970 --> 08:33.513
Can't be knocking
on wrong doors all morning.

08:33.555 --> 08:35.807
Hey, Billy, relax.
It says "Knox" right there.

08:35.849 --> 08:38.644
Knocking for Knox.
Hey, all right.

08:38.685 --> 08:40.354
(clears throat)

08:41.855 --> 08:43.232
(door opens)

08:43.273 --> 08:45.651
Uh, Sholto Macdonald sent us.

08:45.692 --> 08:47.694
-(metal clicks)
-(door creaks)

08:50.155 --> 08:52.658
Up!

08:55.744 --> 08:57.454
(door closes)

08:57.496 --> 08:59.498
(grunting, panting)

09:06.630 --> 09:09.800
KNOX:
Hmm.

09:09.841 --> 09:12.052
Not a speck of dirt.

09:12.094 --> 09:14.096
(sniffing)

09:14.137 --> 09:16.098
No rot...

09:16.139 --> 09:18.934
(sniffs)
beyond the alcohol,

09:18.976 --> 09:22.312
which I'm sure
all of you have taken.

09:22.354 --> 09:24.731
The world in Scotland
may be very different

09:24.773 --> 09:27.609
from what you're used to
in Dublin, lads.

09:27.651 --> 09:30.237
Uh, sorry, sir.

09:30.279 --> 09:31.780
I'm from Urney.

09:31.822 --> 09:35.200
Well, Dublin, Urney, Cork.

09:35.242 --> 09:37.494
You're all the same
over there, aren't you?

09:37.536 --> 09:38.870
(chuckles)

09:38.912 --> 09:41.415
Scotland's place
in the world depends

09:41.456 --> 09:45.961
on the advances we make
for our humble audiences

09:46.003 --> 09:49.798
right here
in this operating theatre.

09:55.304 --> 09:56.555
Oh.

09:56.596 --> 09:59.099
-Whoa.
-Dropsy.

09:59.141 --> 10:01.560
Ah, ha.

10:01.601 --> 10:03.145
Delicious.

10:03.186 --> 10:07.899
You see, you may not have
medicine in, uh, Dublin,

10:07.941 --> 10:10.736
which is why you all come
running over here

10:10.777 --> 10:12.612
like little foxes.

10:12.654 --> 10:16.074
But we do.

10:16.116 --> 10:19.745
And a body like this
will help us cure

10:19.786 --> 10:22.247
a condition like this.

10:22.289 --> 10:25.292
You, boy, bottle this up.

10:27.836 --> 10:31.590
And you, pay these men.

10:31.631 --> 10:35.761
Seven pounds and 14 shillings.

10:44.728 --> 10:47.606
Oh, and, gentlemen.

10:47.647 --> 10:53.403
If you have any more
in this pristine condition,

10:53.445 --> 10:58.367
I will compensate you
more than adequately.

11:09.378 --> 11:11.380
(crowd cheering in distance)

11:18.428 --> 11:20.180
-You screwed me last night.
-Oh.

11:20.222 --> 11:22.224
I thought I could count on you!

11:22.265 --> 11:25.227
Fat man, here,
have a pint. Here.

11:25.268 --> 11:27.604
Apologies for not
showing up, right?

11:27.646 --> 11:29.231
But as Lord as my witness,

11:29.272 --> 11:31.149
we did not resurrect
a single soul last night.

11:31.191 --> 11:32.818
SHOLTO: So where'd you get
the money, then?

11:32.859 --> 11:34.820
Donald. Jamie.

11:34.861 --> 11:36.446
None? How do you live, boy?

11:36.488 --> 11:39.074
-Here, Jamie, lad.
-Aye. Milk it is.

11:39.116 --> 11:40.742
-Hey! Hey! Hey!
-(crowd cheering)

11:40.784 --> 11:43.995
Cheers, to all ye filthy Scots!

11:44.037 --> 11:46.665
-Yeah!
-(cheering)

11:49.084 --> 11:52.629
Who the hell is Donald?

11:52.671 --> 11:55.173
"Was" Donald.

11:55.215 --> 11:57.926
Good friend. Was.

11:59.428 --> 12:01.054
(laughs)

12:03.056 --> 12:05.517
(rooster crows in distance)

12:05.559 --> 12:08.353
-PUNCH: Ah! I hate you!
-JUDY: Well, I hate you more.

12:08.395 --> 12:10.772
PUNCH: Ah, come here, ha!
(snickering)

12:10.814 --> 12:12.482
(laughter)

12:12.524 --> 12:14.943
Judy, did you hear
that if you're buried,

12:14.985 --> 12:16.653
-you might not meet your maker?
-Oh?

12:16.695 --> 12:19.406
-Yes. Come here.
-♪ Da, da-da, da-da, da-da. ♪

12:19.448 --> 12:20.866
(bell dings)

12:24.870 --> 12:26.872
-(laughter)
-What was that for?

12:26.913 --> 12:28.331
PUNCH: I wanted to see
what would happen

12:28.373 --> 12:30.041
if I had to bury you.

12:30.083 --> 12:32.043
JUDY: I'd be at rest
and my soul would go to Heaven.

12:32.085 --> 12:33.253
-PUNCH: Hell.
-JUDY: Heaven.

12:33.295 --> 12:35.213
-Heaven.
-Hell.

12:35.255 --> 12:38.216
PUNCH: But some people
will not get that pleasure.

12:38.258 --> 12:39.759
JUDY:
Oh?

12:39.801 --> 12:41.386
Indeed. They're called
resurrectionists.

12:41.428 --> 12:42.846
Resu-what?

12:47.392 --> 12:49.352
-(laughter)
-Grave robbers, Judy.

12:49.394 --> 12:51.354
-Nobody is safe.
-JUDY: But why not use

12:51.396 --> 12:53.440
all the dead bodies
that die from sickness?

12:53.482 --> 12:56.193
Because they can only use
the bodies of criminals.

12:56.234 --> 12:58.028
It's the law!

12:58.069 --> 13:00.405
So they can
definitely use yours.

13:00.447 --> 13:02.282
Uh-huh.

13:03.283 --> 13:05.869
-(laughter)
-BURKE: Hey.

13:05.911 --> 13:07.913
We have work to do.

13:12.417 --> 13:14.419
♪ ♪

13:23.345 --> 13:29.142
You seem quieter than normal,
and that's saying something.

13:29.184 --> 13:31.186
I don't like it.

13:31.228 --> 13:33.855
What, the money?

13:33.897 --> 13:37.359
-Playing God.
-Billy.

13:37.400 --> 13:39.319
We're two Irish immigrants
sitting in a pub

13:39.361 --> 13:44.157
on a Sunday afternoon
when most people are in church.

13:44.199 --> 13:46.159
There ain't nothing God-like
about any of this.

13:46.201 --> 13:48.662
(exhales) 'Tisn't right.

13:48.703 --> 13:50.330
ABIGAIL:
Something wet, if you would.

13:50.372 --> 13:54.584
(hacking, coughing, retching)

13:54.626 --> 13:57.796
Hey, hey. Kindly keep all
your consumption to yourself.

14:08.974 --> 14:11.768
It ain't dropsy, but she's
still got to be worth more

14:11.810 --> 14:13.812
than the average healthy whore.

14:19.943 --> 14:22.153
Wet enough?

14:23.655 --> 14:26.199
-Nope.
-Allow me to rectify that.

14:26.241 --> 14:29.411
-My name is William Burke.
-Abigail Simpson.

14:29.452 --> 14:33.456
-(retches, coughs)
-Ugh.

14:33.498 --> 14:35.166
-(chuckles)
-(retching)

14:35.208 --> 14:37.252
Oh, that's a nasty cough
you got.

14:37.294 --> 14:40.505
(chuckles) And in this cold,
you could catch your death.

14:40.547 --> 14:42.507
You know? Ah, shit.

14:42.549 --> 14:47.596
Ain't no cold, and you know it.

14:47.637 --> 14:49.639
My condolences, then.

14:49.681 --> 14:51.558
Don't want your...

14:51.600 --> 14:55.228
condol... condol...

14:55.270 --> 14:57.314
What you said.

14:57.355 --> 15:01.318
In that case, how about another?

15:01.359 --> 15:04.613
-(chuckling)
-Eh? (laughing)

15:04.654 --> 15:07.490
♪ ♪

15:07.532 --> 15:10.285
-Mmm.
-(sighs)

15:10.327 --> 15:11.911
-(coughing)
-(laughing)

15:14.372 --> 15:16.166
(laughing)

15:19.502 --> 15:23.048
Whiskey! (laughs)

15:23.089 --> 15:24.799
Angus, here.

15:28.720 --> 15:30.722
(whoops)

15:36.061 --> 15:37.604
Oh!

15:41.107 --> 15:42.942
(laughing)

15:44.235 --> 15:46.488
(incoherent mumbling)

15:46.529 --> 15:49.908
Boys, get her out of here
before she's a corpse!

15:49.949 --> 15:51.618
Wouldn't want that, huh?

15:51.660 --> 15:54.329
-(incoherent mumbling)
-(straining)

15:54.371 --> 15:55.789
Okay.

16:01.503 --> 16:04.047
(Abigail hacking, retching)

16:04.089 --> 16:06.341
Where'd you say you lived again?

16:06.383 --> 16:08.593
The floor. I can find it myself.

16:08.635 --> 16:10.387
-HARE: Wh-What are you doing?
-BURKE: Hey.

16:10.428 --> 16:12.055
She's not gonna make it
through the night.

16:12.097 --> 16:14.391
Yeah, the night's
hardly done, and...

16:14.432 --> 16:15.850
That's why you were
doing all this,

16:15.892 --> 16:17.435
why you brought her
all the drinks?

16:17.477 --> 16:19.145
Billy, it's an investment, okay?
She's not gonna...

16:19.187 --> 16:22.023
-So much for your investment.
-Shit!

16:22.065 --> 16:24.567
Hey, Liam! Liam, come back!

16:29.656 --> 16:31.116
(shushes)

16:32.909 --> 16:34.911
(coughing)

16:41.918 --> 16:43.545
(whispers):
Come on.

16:47.507 --> 16:49.134
All but embalmed.

16:50.802 --> 16:52.679
Yet still drawing breath.

16:52.721 --> 16:54.889
(Burke grunts)

16:54.931 --> 16:56.891
(panting)

16:56.933 --> 16:58.893
I could use a bit of help.

16:58.935 --> 17:01.896
-You've lost your mind.
-Seven pounds, Billy!

17:01.938 --> 17:04.399
Seven pounds, and you want
to give it up for this drunk?!

17:04.441 --> 17:06.025
Now who's lost his mind?!

17:08.027 --> 17:09.863
Fine!

17:14.784 --> 17:16.786
Fine. (chuckles)

17:20.457 --> 17:23.209
Ah... Oh, God.

17:23.251 --> 17:24.669
(sighs, groans)

17:31.050 --> 17:33.052
-(straining)
-(muffled groaning)

17:38.057 --> 17:40.435
-Jesus! Oh, no, no, no.
-No! No! No!

17:40.477 --> 17:42.812
(coughing, screaming)

17:42.854 --> 17:44.105
Billy!

17:44.147 --> 17:46.775
-Billy!
-Get off! Get off!

17:46.816 --> 17:48.943
Get off me!

17:48.985 --> 17:50.987
(muffled screaming)

17:51.029 --> 17:53.031
(straining loudly)

18:02.373 --> 18:05.210
(straining loudly)

18:05.251 --> 18:07.253
(muffled groaning quiets)

18:12.258 --> 18:14.219
(muffled groaning stops)

18:22.268 --> 18:24.270
(panting)

18:30.610 --> 18:32.362
-What the hell was that?!
-Shh!

18:32.403 --> 18:36.074
Shush! Shh.

18:36.115 --> 18:38.117
Shh!

18:43.289 --> 18:45.124
Science.

18:47.502 --> 18:49.087
Hey. Help me up with it.

18:49.128 --> 18:50.630
Billy!

18:50.672 --> 18:53.299
Yeah, yeah, yeah. (grunts)

18:53.341 --> 18:56.386
(panting):
Okay. Okay. Okay.

19:04.936 --> 19:09.190
And what am I supposed to do
with this?

19:09.232 --> 19:10.608
Aye.

19:10.650 --> 19:13.486
Her head's a bit mussed,
but the rest,

19:13.528 --> 19:15.572
totally fresh and, um,

19:15.613 --> 19:18.116
clean-ish, except
for the consumption bit,

19:18.157 --> 19:20.660
which I assumed that you'd want?

19:20.702 --> 19:23.830
Yes, yes, yes, but the face...

19:23.872 --> 19:26.791
No matter how pristine the rest
of the body may be underneath,

19:26.833 --> 19:30.128
the face is the first thing
these students will see,

19:30.169 --> 19:32.755
and they may not believe
that the rest of the body

19:32.797 --> 19:34.173
doesn't follow suit.

19:34.215 --> 19:36.634
My recent samples,

19:36.676 --> 19:39.929
though purchased
at a discount price,

19:39.971 --> 19:44.142
have put me in fourth place
in a three horse race.

19:44.183 --> 19:46.895
This is all about

19:46.936 --> 19:51.316
research and performance,
gentlemen.

19:51.357 --> 19:55.320
If I can't show this body to the
rest of the medical community,

19:55.361 --> 19:58.907
if I can't perform
with the best samples

19:58.948 --> 20:03.536
and further my discoveries,
then this lot will leave

20:03.578 --> 20:05.622
and go to a competitor's
operating theatre

20:05.663 --> 20:08.917
with better... wares.

20:08.958 --> 20:13.546
And this, all of this,

20:13.588 --> 20:18.801
my life's work,
will cease to exist.

20:20.803 --> 20:23.473
And I will not have that!

20:25.016 --> 20:28.144
Do you cretins understand?

20:28.186 --> 20:29.687
Uh-huh. (clears throat)

20:31.648 --> 20:33.483
Yeah. Mm-hmm.

20:33.524 --> 20:36.569
Good.

20:36.611 --> 20:39.405
In civilized countries,

20:39.447 --> 20:43.409
this is what we call
an understanding.

20:43.451 --> 20:46.245
We now have an understanding.

20:48.790 --> 20:50.959
You only get six pounds

20:51.000 --> 20:54.045
and a free lesson in
what we in Scotland consider

20:54.087 --> 20:56.297
-the work ethic.
-(bell dings)

20:56.339 --> 20:58.424
Quality counts, gentlemen.

20:58.466 --> 21:01.177
Do not let your Irish roots
get in the way

21:01.219 --> 21:03.262
of doing a good job here.

21:05.890 --> 21:09.352
-Mm.
Oh, and, gentlemen.

21:14.524 --> 21:20.446
(quietly): Be very careful
how you acquire the merchandise.

21:20.488 --> 21:22.824
I don't want coppers
around here.

21:22.865 --> 21:27.829
They're much better suited
to your part of the town.

21:27.870 --> 21:29.872
Now begone.

21:34.711 --> 21:38.297
-(lively music playing)
-(crowd cheering)

21:42.135 --> 21:44.137
BURKE:
You don't talk much, do you?

21:46.180 --> 21:48.558
I've heard you two
are the life of the party.

21:48.599 --> 21:50.893
Let's have a good time.

21:50.935 --> 21:53.730
HARE: Far from the confines of
the Charity, aren't you, love?

21:53.771 --> 21:57.275
-I go where the work is.
-This is where the work isn't.

21:57.316 --> 22:00.987
-Too much woman for you?
-Too much for the woman.

22:01.029 --> 22:03.614
Off you run. Plenty of suitors
looking to ruin you proper.

22:05.324 --> 22:07.827
-(glass shatters)
-(music stops)

22:07.869 --> 22:09.454
Look at this miserable shite!

22:13.875 --> 22:17.545
What in the name of all that
is holy is that hideous thing?

22:19.338 --> 22:20.715
The boy doesn't talk.

22:20.757 --> 22:23.301
Oh, he can't even talk
out of that hole, chin face?

22:23.342 --> 22:25.511
Disfigured and mute,
you scabby roaster?

22:25.553 --> 22:27.972
-INNKEEPER: Hey! Hey!
-(sobbing)

22:28.014 --> 22:29.432
Get her out of here!

22:29.474 --> 22:30.933
-Get out of here!
-(crowd shouting)

22:33.686 --> 22:35.438
-HARE: Hey.
-Get out of here!

22:38.024 --> 22:39.984
All right, boy.
You're all right, boy.

22:40.026 --> 22:41.152
You're all right.

22:41.194 --> 22:43.404
Somebody take care of him.

22:45.406 --> 22:47.909
M'lady! M'lady!

22:47.950 --> 22:51.454
Ah. Apologies. Ah.

22:51.496 --> 22:53.456
We shouldn't have let them
treat you like that.

22:53.498 --> 22:55.500
So, uh...

22:58.002 --> 22:59.796
Apology accepted.

22:59.837 --> 23:01.506
-(laughs): Oh.
-Lead the way.

23:01.547 --> 23:03.007
-(giggling)
-(growls)

23:03.049 --> 23:05.259
HARE:
Hey! What's going on?

23:05.301 --> 23:09.680
Just gonna let off some steam.
Nothing to worry about.

23:09.722 --> 23:11.724
(both laughing)

23:18.689 --> 23:20.691
♪ ♪

23:32.203 --> 23:34.747
Oy! You afraid of me, are you?

23:37.917 --> 23:40.211
What about you?

23:42.130 --> 23:43.923
(chuckles)

23:43.965 --> 23:45.299
(gasps)

23:45.341 --> 23:47.593
Oh, so you like it rough?
(laughs)

23:51.389 --> 23:54.350
Oy! Hey. Let go.

23:56.352 --> 23:58.187
Mm.

23:58.229 --> 24:00.731
Billy, remember,

24:00.773 --> 24:03.442
quality matters.

24:06.070 --> 24:10.741
Miss, my name is William Burke.

24:10.783 --> 24:14.912
This here is my partner,
Billy Hare.

24:14.954 --> 24:17.665
MARY:
I don't care, boys.

24:17.707 --> 24:19.876
BURKE:
Good.

24:19.917 --> 24:22.837
Where was I?

24:22.879 --> 24:26.174
Ah, yes. Like this.

24:26.215 --> 24:27.884
(shrieks)

24:27.925 --> 24:30.261
(muffled screaming)

24:30.303 --> 24:32.263
Billy! Hop on!

24:32.305 --> 24:33.639
Hop on!

24:33.681 --> 24:35.683
(muffled screaming continues)

24:55.494 --> 24:57.496
-(muffled crying)
-(grunting)

25:06.088 --> 25:08.090
(muffled grunting)

25:24.565 --> 25:26.567
(muffled grunting quiets)

25:34.575 --> 25:36.577
-(muffled grunting stops)
-(panting)

26:00.184 --> 26:01.769
(bell dings)

26:07.483 --> 26:09.610
He's doing well for himself.

26:09.652 --> 26:13.072
'Cause of us, mate.

26:13.114 --> 26:15.825
KNOX: The effects
of prostitution on the body

26:15.866 --> 26:17.493
and their diseases.

26:17.535 --> 26:19.537
♪ ♪

26:33.884 --> 26:35.344
-Here we go.
-There we go.

26:35.386 --> 26:36.721
-BURKE: Hare?
-Yeah, yeah.

26:42.101 --> 26:43.769
(bell dings)

26:43.811 --> 26:47.857
KNOX:
The effects of alcohol.

26:47.898 --> 26:49.900
-(crowd cheering)
-(pounding on table)

26:52.069 --> 26:54.572
-(bell dinging)
-Hey!

26:54.613 --> 26:57.033
-(laughs)
-How are you, love?

26:57.074 --> 26:59.952
-Is that your house?
-(giggling)

26:59.994 --> 27:01.996
-Whoa-oh!
-(screaming, laughing)

27:05.624 --> 27:08.002
(bell dings)

27:08.044 --> 27:11.213
(laughing)

27:11.255 --> 27:14.091
Hey, don't run off with her.

27:14.133 --> 27:16.427
-Come on.
-(grunting)

27:20.306 --> 27:23.434
KNOX:
Comparable ages and body types.

27:23.476 --> 27:26.312
We can use one as a control.

27:26.354 --> 27:28.356
♪ ♪

27:33.444 --> 27:35.946
There's not a speck
of dirt on you two.

27:35.988 --> 27:37.656
-Science.
-Science.

27:45.164 --> 27:47.166
-(crowd cheering)
-(bell dinging)

28:01.138 --> 28:04.308
Here's to Billy Hare
and Liam Burke!

28:04.350 --> 28:06.352
(laughs)

28:06.394 --> 28:08.354
Oh!

28:08.396 --> 28:10.398
♪ ♪

28:22.243 --> 28:24.245
(coughing)

28:27.498 --> 28:29.959
It's a bit late
for a child to be out.

28:30.000 --> 28:31.669
What do you suppose he's worth?

28:31.710 --> 28:33.546
Nothing.

28:33.587 --> 28:35.548
Yeah, you're right.

28:35.589 --> 28:37.591
People would know.

28:39.635 --> 28:41.637
You think that's the problem?

28:43.264 --> 28:46.058
(scoffs)

28:46.100 --> 28:48.102
What?

28:50.312 --> 28:52.314
Hey.

28:55.109 --> 28:57.111
♪ ♪

29:05.536 --> 29:09.081
(muffled whimpering)

29:09.123 --> 29:11.333
(muffled scream)

29:13.419 --> 29:15.421
(bell dings)

29:35.900 --> 29:37.651
(groans)

29:40.779 --> 29:42.573
(sighs)

29:42.615 --> 29:44.575
Where you going to?

29:44.617 --> 29:46.327
You go ahead.

29:46.368 --> 29:48.871
(sniffles)
I need to get some fresh air.

29:48.913 --> 29:50.873
And a bed.

29:50.915 --> 29:53.292
(laughs):
Ah, ha, ha!

29:53.334 --> 29:57.338
Someone's going
to the Charity shop, hey?

29:57.379 --> 30:01.550
Hey, don't let them
overcharge you this time, Billy!

30:01.592 --> 30:04.803
Billy! Billy!

30:07.806 --> 30:09.808
-(Punch and Judy grunting)
-(thunder rumbles softly)

30:15.481 --> 30:18.025
PUNCH:
Judy, do you know what I hate?

30:18.067 --> 30:19.985
Me?

30:20.027 --> 30:22.738
Yes, but that's only because
you're my wife.

30:22.780 --> 30:24.782
-(Judy grunting)
-(crowd gasping)

30:28.160 --> 30:29.662
I deserved that.

30:29.703 --> 30:33.082
-JUDY: Who else, then?
-The Irish. And doctors.

30:33.123 --> 30:35.167
PUPPET KNOX (echoing):
Did somebody call a doctor?

30:35.209 --> 30:38.003
-(Judy shrieks)
-PUNCH: Ah! Oh, Lord! He's here!

30:38.045 --> 30:39.755
Which means we're not.

30:41.382 --> 30:44.969
(echoing): Now, now,
why would you run from me?

30:45.010 --> 30:48.472
My only lot in life is to make
all of your lives better.

30:48.514 --> 30:51.892
I am but a humble servant.

30:51.934 --> 30:54.353
-(crowd booing)
-(thunder rumbling)

30:55.771 --> 30:57.648
Don't take my word.

30:57.690 --> 31:00.651
Listen to my two best friends.

31:00.693 --> 31:03.571
Mr. Burke, Mr. Hare.

31:03.612 --> 31:07.700
My good Irish friends,
welcome back.

31:07.741 --> 31:10.286
What have you been up to?

31:10.327 --> 31:13.122
PUPPET HARE: Spending all
me money on women and wine.

31:13.163 --> 31:16.834
-PUPPET KNOX: And I've given you
a lot of money.
-Mm-hmm.

31:16.875 --> 31:19.503
-BOTH: Thank you, Doctor.
-Don't mention it.

31:19.545 --> 31:23.007
-I mean that. Don't mention it.
-(thunder rumbling)

31:23.048 --> 31:25.092
PUPPET HARE:
What about you, Billy?

31:25.134 --> 31:27.011
Are you going to mention it?

31:27.052 --> 31:29.388
PUPPET BURKE:
Oh, imagine you did.

31:29.430 --> 31:32.016
-We'd both hang.
-Or maybe that would be better.

31:32.057 --> 31:35.561
(echoing):
Then at least you could sleep.

31:35.603 --> 31:37.688
PUPPET KNOX:
On my table.

31:37.730 --> 31:39.815
-(laughter)
-(puppets laughing)

31:43.694 --> 31:45.404
PUPPET HARE:
Good luck sleeping, Billy!

31:45.446 --> 31:47.364
PUPPET KNOX:
Nighty night, Billy!

31:47.406 --> 31:49.158
(puppets laughing)

31:51.201 --> 31:53.746
-(lively music playing)
-(sighs, sniffs)

31:53.787 --> 31:55.789
All hail the walking dead.

31:57.249 --> 32:00.210
Not tonight. Just let me drink.

32:00.252 --> 32:02.546
I'll buy you a drink.
I'll buy you four.

32:02.588 --> 32:04.965
How 'bout you stop waving
your, uh, money around?

32:05.007 --> 32:06.842
You think people haven't
noticed your new coat?

32:06.884 --> 32:08.886
The fact that every meal
is at a restaurant?

32:08.927 --> 32:12.181
The fact that you bedded
half the whores in the city?

32:12.222 --> 32:13.849
Billy, I thought
you were more worried

32:13.891 --> 32:15.309
about your own eternal soul.

32:15.351 --> 32:17.645
Who says I ain't?

32:17.686 --> 32:19.897
But you wouldn't know
about that, would ya?

32:19.938 --> 32:21.899
-Listen...
-No.

32:21.940 --> 32:24.568
No, no, no. You listen.

32:24.610 --> 32:26.570
You may not care
about sin and damnation,

32:26.612 --> 32:28.614
-but you care about
getting caught, don't ya?
-Billy...

32:28.656 --> 32:30.407
You call me Billy again,

32:30.449 --> 32:33.202
and you'll be doing it
without teeth.

32:37.873 --> 32:41.335
William, it's clear to me
that you're in a foul mood,

32:41.377 --> 32:44.380
so I'm gonna let this one pass.

32:44.421 --> 32:46.382
But remember this:

32:46.423 --> 32:51.679
sin or not, it's all us
getting caught, not just me.

32:51.720 --> 32:54.932
It's all us.

32:54.973 --> 32:58.727
Now who wants to play
on my bagpipe?!

33:12.783 --> 33:14.785
♪ ♪

33:40.269 --> 33:44.106
Angus, all of Billy's drinks
are on me.

33:45.733 --> 33:47.735
♪ ♪

33:55.826 --> 33:58.746
Hey. Listen. Hey.

33:58.787 --> 34:01.039
It's fine.

34:01.081 --> 34:03.167
You know...

34:03.208 --> 34:06.128
you know you're like
a brother to me? Hmm?

34:06.170 --> 34:07.921
HARE:
I said it's fine, mate.

34:07.963 --> 34:09.798
BURKE:
I love you.

34:11.508 --> 34:13.469
(bell dings)

34:13.510 --> 34:15.721
-Nightcap.
-(bell dings)

34:15.763 --> 34:18.724
And you're broke.

34:18.766 --> 34:20.893
Fine.

34:20.934 --> 34:24.146
Let's get it over with
before I pass out on top of him.

34:26.523 --> 34:28.484
(sputters)

34:28.525 --> 34:30.486
(sighs)

34:30.527 --> 34:32.112
(grunting)

34:34.448 --> 34:36.867
-BURKE: Oh, shit!
-HARE: Jamie, Jamie!

34:36.909 --> 34:39.578
It's us! It's us! It's us!

34:39.620 --> 34:40.871
(grunting)

34:43.916 --> 34:45.501
Jamie!

34:55.469 --> 34:58.180
-(shouts)
-(grunting)

34:58.222 --> 35:02.142
I'll tell... me mother!

35:04.603 --> 35:06.563
(Jamie grunting loudly)

35:06.605 --> 35:08.607
♪ ♪

35:17.616 --> 35:20.828
No! No! No!

35:20.869 --> 35:22.287
No!

35:23.622 --> 35:24.998
No.

35:25.040 --> 35:27.125
(grunting)

35:29.127 --> 35:32.130
(shouts)

35:36.260 --> 35:38.262
(panting)

35:45.310 --> 35:47.312
♪ ♪

36:06.456 --> 36:08.458
♪ ♪

36:12.379 --> 36:14.840
Down.

36:14.882 --> 36:16.884
Up.

36:25.225 --> 36:27.311
(knocking)

36:36.695 --> 36:39.072
(sighs)

36:39.114 --> 36:40.741
Leave.

36:48.206 --> 36:50.584
(door closes)

36:50.626 --> 36:53.879
This is unacceptable.

36:53.921 --> 36:56.173
This body is...

36:56.214 --> 36:58.634
disfigured.

37:00.218 --> 37:02.220
A horror.

37:04.640 --> 37:07.559
It's almost worthless.

37:15.734 --> 37:19.196
I ask you to do one thing.

37:24.785 --> 37:26.578
Pristine.

37:26.620 --> 37:29.539
(sawing)

37:35.504 --> 37:37.214
(grunts)

37:37.255 --> 37:39.675
(sighs)

37:41.843 --> 37:45.681
I will dispose of the rest.

37:45.722 --> 37:49.685
These... pieces,
get rid of them.

37:56.608 --> 37:58.568
(grunts)

38:03.365 --> 38:04.866
-(fabric tearing)
-(grunting)

38:15.210 --> 38:17.295
Not even a shilling?

38:17.337 --> 38:19.381
Go.

38:19.423 --> 38:21.133
Yeah, okay.

38:21.174 --> 38:25.095
KNOX:
And be careful.

38:25.137 --> 38:27.973
That head...

38:28.015 --> 38:30.600
will tend to prove the rumors
I've been hearing

38:30.642 --> 38:34.730
about murderers
walking the streets,

38:34.771 --> 38:37.774
if you can believe it.

38:39.985 --> 38:44.740
And I can't be a party
to murder.

38:44.781 --> 38:48.035
Do we have an understanding?

38:48.076 --> 38:50.078
Aye.

38:57.586 --> 38:59.588
For science.

39:04.009 --> 39:06.011
Science.

39:14.061 --> 39:16.063
(insects chittering)

39:29.451 --> 39:31.453
Fancy a pint?

39:37.042 --> 39:40.003
Jesus Christ.

39:49.471 --> 39:51.473
I'm done.

39:55.435 --> 39:57.437
-(thunder rumbling softly)
-(laughter)

39:57.479 --> 39:59.439
♪ ♪

40:18.500 --> 40:20.502
(laughter fades)

40:25.549 --> 40:27.968
PUPPET BURKE (echoing):
What's the matter, Billy?

40:28.009 --> 40:29.886
Cat got your tongue?

40:29.928 --> 40:32.389
Doctor got your foot? (laughs)

40:32.430 --> 40:34.391
PUPPET HARE:
Let's ask him again, shall we?

40:34.432 --> 40:38.353
Ooh, Doctor?

40:38.395 --> 40:41.356
PUPPET KNOX: People are
starting to ask questions.

40:41.398 --> 40:43.650
Did you think
you could just leave?

40:43.692 --> 40:46.194
He thought he could just leave.

40:46.236 --> 40:47.779
We saved you a seat.

40:58.123 --> 41:00.709
...tell... me mother!

41:03.587 --> 41:05.422
You're going to hang, Billy,

41:05.463 --> 41:09.718
whether you stop now or you kill
a hundred more Daft Jamies,

41:09.759 --> 41:13.763
or maybe some of these people.

41:17.642 --> 41:20.228
Quality, Billy. Or...

41:20.270 --> 41:24.149
PUPPETS:
I'll tell me mother!

41:24.191 --> 41:26.151
JAMIE (echoing):
...mother!

41:26.193 --> 41:29.613
CROWD (in unison):
I'll tell me mother!

41:29.654 --> 41:31.114
Stop this right now!

41:33.491 --> 41:35.493
♪ ♪

41:46.087 --> 41:48.048
(quiet chatter, laughter)

41:48.089 --> 41:50.091
♪ ♪

42:02.312 --> 42:03.730
(sighs)

42:15.242 --> 42:17.160
(laughs):
H-Hey!

42:17.202 --> 42:19.246
I thought you'd be
in Cork by now.

42:19.287 --> 42:21.122
I should be. You're right.

42:21.164 --> 42:23.208
But you don't want to.
Huh? Not really.

42:23.250 --> 42:27.003
I do. I really do. Liam.

42:27.045 --> 42:29.047
Oh, no-no-no.

42:29.089 --> 42:31.758
Listen, um...

42:31.800 --> 42:34.511
I ran into my cousin Margaret.

42:34.552 --> 42:38.765
She's in town, and, well, uh,
it got me thinking.

42:38.807 --> 42:44.062
Family, friends,
that's what matters.

42:44.104 --> 42:46.106
Right, that's great.

42:46.147 --> 42:49.776
No, no, no, no, no, no.
William, come with me.

42:49.818 --> 42:52.153
-You know how awkward I can get.
-You?

42:52.195 --> 42:53.905
(laughs) Right.

42:53.947 --> 42:58.285
But family's a different
kind of beast, mate.

42:58.326 --> 43:01.496
Come have a drink with us.

43:01.538 --> 43:03.540
Just family.

43:07.544 --> 43:09.546
Come on.

43:09.587 --> 43:12.465
♪ ♪

43:16.344 --> 43:18.346
(chuckles)

43:20.390 --> 43:22.350
(Burke sighs)

43:22.392 --> 43:25.061
HARE:
That's not the way to your flat.

43:25.103 --> 43:26.730
Well, the Grays are out of town.

43:26.771 --> 43:28.523
They asked me
to keep an eye out.

43:28.565 --> 43:30.191
It's better than
our dirty flops.

43:33.111 --> 43:35.655
Fine.

43:35.697 --> 43:38.074
(laughs)

43:38.116 --> 43:39.951
Cousin,

43:39.993 --> 43:43.371
meet my dearest friend,
William Hare,

43:43.413 --> 43:45.290
of Londonderry.

43:45.332 --> 43:47.417
William, my cousin Margaret.

43:47.459 --> 43:50.378
-How do you do?
-I... (sighs)

43:52.380 --> 43:54.632
-Pleasure.
-BURKE: Speaking of,

43:54.674 --> 43:56.676
I come bearing drinks.

43:56.718 --> 43:59.095
-(sets bottle down)
-Huh?

44:01.681 --> 44:03.892
Family.

44:03.933 --> 44:06.811
It's all we really have.

44:11.608 --> 44:15.153
Oh! Right.

44:15.195 --> 44:18.114
(sighs) I need some space
for my bladder.

44:26.998 --> 44:29.751
So, uh...

44:29.793 --> 44:32.670
cousins, huh?

44:32.712 --> 44:35.423
-When was the last time ya...
-Oh, well,

44:35.465 --> 44:37.926
to be perfectly honest,
I can't quite place him.

44:37.967 --> 44:41.262
I only just arrived
in Edinburgh two days ago,

44:41.304 --> 44:44.516
but he seemed so convinced and
sweet, I felt maybe I was off.

44:44.557 --> 44:47.102
-Seemed convinced, did he?
-Of our relation.

44:47.143 --> 44:49.479
I do see it in the eyes a bit.

44:49.521 --> 44:51.648
Oh, I see something, too.

44:51.689 --> 44:53.650
Clearly.

44:53.691 --> 44:55.568
Forgive me, Margaret.

44:55.610 --> 44:58.822
Seems nature is
screaming my name as well.

45:01.616 --> 45:03.618
(panting)

45:10.083 --> 45:13.253
-You lying sack of shite!
-Easy there, Billy.

45:13.294 --> 45:16.214
Wouldn't want Margaret to hear,
now, would... (grunts)

45:16.256 --> 45:17.924
That's for calling me Billy,

45:17.966 --> 45:20.343
and for lying to me and pulling
me back into your madness.

45:20.385 --> 45:23.263
-I told you I was done!
-Now who's lying?

45:23.304 --> 45:26.224
William, you knew exactly where
this little reunion would end.

45:26.266 --> 45:28.643
You like it. You just don't like
that you like it.

45:28.685 --> 45:30.019
Stop!

45:30.061 --> 45:32.689
16. 16 so far.

45:32.730 --> 45:34.399
Men, women, Jamie.

45:34.441 --> 45:37.068
-Stop.
-It's me or her, Billy.

45:37.110 --> 45:39.112
Her we can explain, but me?

45:39.154 --> 45:40.864
That'll be 17
on your conscience,

45:40.905 --> 45:44.576
and you'll hang
for every single one of us.

45:59.757 --> 46:01.759
♪ ♪

46:11.478 --> 46:14.481
(Margaret crying,
muffled screaming)

46:17.025 --> 46:19.027
(muffled crying continues)

46:21.946 --> 46:25.617
God our Father,
your power brings us to birth.

46:25.658 --> 46:29.078
Your providence
guides our lives.

46:29.120 --> 46:32.832
And, by your command,
we return to dust.

46:32.874 --> 46:34.876
(muffled crying stops)

46:49.891 --> 46:51.893
(panting)

46:54.812 --> 46:58.983
She needs to be out
before the sun's up.

46:59.025 --> 47:01.736
All right.

47:01.778 --> 47:04.656
(grunts, sighs)

47:09.994 --> 47:11.996
(sighs)

47:19.295 --> 47:21.339
It's not even midnight yet.

47:21.381 --> 47:25.343
Um, rest yourself for an hour
or two, and, uh,

47:25.385 --> 47:27.345
we'll move her then, yeah?

47:27.387 --> 47:29.389
♪ ♪

47:52.954 --> 47:54.956
♪ ♪

48:16.894 --> 48:18.896
♪ ♪

48:48.134 --> 48:50.136
♪ ♪

49:01.981 --> 49:04.192
(whistles blowing)

49:24.087 --> 49:27.048
(yelling)

49:47.485 --> 49:49.487
♪ ♪

50:11.926 --> 50:15.346
PUPPET HARE: We were charged
with 16 counts of murder.

50:15.388 --> 50:18.433
PUPPET BURKE: Interesting.
How'd they find out?

50:18.474 --> 50:19.934
PUPPET HARE:
Well...

50:19.976 --> 50:22.353
I told them.

50:22.395 --> 50:24.397
PUPPET BURKE:
What?! (grunting)

50:24.439 --> 50:26.774
(choking)

50:26.816 --> 50:29.527
(panting, coughing)

50:29.569 --> 50:32.405
So we were both hanged?

50:32.447 --> 50:34.949
PUPPET HARE:
Well... not quite.

50:34.991 --> 50:37.660
PUPPET BURKE:
What do you mean, "not quite"?

50:37.702 --> 50:39.871
PUPPET HARE:
Well, the thing is, Liam,

50:39.912 --> 50:41.748
I turned King's evidence.

50:46.544 --> 50:48.254
No.

50:48.296 --> 50:51.591
I confessed in exchange
for immunity.

50:53.176 --> 50:57.054
They wanted to punish someone,
so I made a deal.

50:58.389 --> 51:00.683
PUPPET BURKE:
So what happened to you?

51:02.685 --> 51:04.896
PUPPET HARE:
Nobody knows.

51:09.025 --> 51:13.696
But we all know what happened
to you, William Burke.

51:13.738 --> 51:19.285
Yes. I was hanged
by the neck until dead.

51:19.327 --> 51:23.581
Yeah. And then your fresh
and mostly pristine corpse...

51:23.623 --> 51:26.793
-Oh, mostly pristine?
-Well, you are Irish.

51:26.834 --> 51:28.586
Right, right. Carry on.

51:28.628 --> 51:30.671
Your corpse still exists today.

51:30.713 --> 51:32.381
(choking)

51:32.423 --> 51:34.425
Ta-da!

51:42.099 --> 51:44.101
♪ ♪

51:55.446 --> 51:57.865
PUPPET HARE: To this day,
William Burke's body

51:57.907 --> 51:59.867
is on display for all to see

51:59.909 --> 52:03.913
at the University of
Edinburgh's Anatomical Museum.

52:03.955 --> 52:06.415
PUPPET BURKE:
Ironically, I've become

52:06.457 --> 52:09.502
the most lucrative corpse
in the history of Scotland.

52:09.544 --> 52:11.546
♪ ♪

52:23.474 --> 52:27.144
PUPPET HARE:
In the name of science.
